<dl id="n53055c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53055c">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53055c"> 55(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> he shall have / not tense enough <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53055c"><li>FW 598.30 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n53055c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n53055c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53055c">MS BL 47488-232v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:042 <a name="tad3" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tad3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad3.htm#n53055c">Draft: IV&sect;1.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[We are short of &hellip; a future sense of prophecy &hellip; We do not have a &lsquo;futurum exactum&rsquo;, the pre-future &hellip; But we do not have the logically-required tense to express a future that is even further away than the future starting point. &hellip; Because of our position in time <mark>we need at least nine clearly-separate tenses to express temporal relationships; yet we have only six tenses</mark>.]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 42</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
